Data Analysis for Ford Gobike System Data by Caleb Denzeil¶

Introduction¶

The ford Gobike dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The dataset has 16 columns and 183412 rows. The columns are:

  • duration_sec - duration time in seconds
  • start_time - starting time
  • end_time - ending time
  • start_station_id - Starting station id
  • start_station_name - The name of the starting station
  • start_station_latitude - Starting station in latitude
  • start_station_longitude - Starting station location in longitude
  • end_station_id - Ending station id
  • end_station_name - Ending station name
  • end_station_latitude -Ending station location in latitude
  • end_station_longitude - Ending station location in longitude
  • bike_id - bike id
  • user_type - User type either Subscriber or Customer
  • member_birth_year - Member birth year
  • member_gender - Member gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip - is the bike used for round trips?

Quality issues¶

  • Start_time and end_time columns are in object format
  • start_station_id,start_station_name,end_station_id,end_station_name, member_birth_year and member_gender have missing values.

Cleaning¶

  • In this section, I will address the quality issues
In [11]:
# Change the start and end_time columns from object to dateformat
def date_conversion(start,end):
    global copy_b
    copy_b[start]=pd.to_datetime(copy_b[start])
    copy_b[end]=pd.to_datetime(copy_b[end])
    
    #create new columns for starting and ending time
    copy_b['Starting_time']=copy_b[start].dt.strftime('Y%-m%-d%')
    copy_b['Ending_time']=copy_b[end].dt.strftime('Y%-m%-d%')
    
    #separate the hours
    copy_b['Start_hour']=copy_b[start].dt.hour
    copy_b['End_hour']=copy_b[end].dt.hour
    
    #separate the days
    copy_b['Start_day']=copy_b[start].dt.strftime('%a')
    copy_b['End_day']=copy_b[end].dt.strftime('%a')
    
    #separate the months
    copy_b['Start_month']=copy_b[start].dt.strftime('%B')
    copy_b['End_month']=copy_b[end].dt.strftime('%B')
    
    copy_b=copy_b.drop(columns=[start,end])

plt.show();

The customers duration is much lower compared to the subscribers¶

The average duration is high on the weekends compared to (Mon-Fri).¶

    • On thursday subscribers and customers show up the most and are less on the weekends(sun and sat)
  • Duration:

    • The customers duration is much lower compared to the subscribers
  • Start_time:
    • From the graph most customers ride between 17 and 18 while subscribers either 8 or 17.
    • From the bar chart, their are more than females, and both males and females show up in high numbers betweeen 8 and 17
